{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582938","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582938"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:01:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:01:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1532"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1532","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1532"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.01,0.01,0.01,0.93]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1532"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86754"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1532","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1532"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1532"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71023"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2770"},{"type":"tags","id":"2843"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5392"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5415"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86754","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86754"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for evaluation of joint pain and swelling present for many years. He has no significant medical history and takes paracetamol as needed. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is bilateral symmetrical swelling of the metacarpophalangeal and proximal interphalangeal joints. The proximal interphalangeal joints show hyperextension while the distal interphalangeal joints are flexed (Image). There is no skin rash or nail changes. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pseudorheumatoid dysplasia","Ehlers-Danlos syndrome","Scleroderma","Psoriatic arthritis","Rheumatoid arthritis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with swan neck deformities, characterised by hyperextension of the proximal interphalangeal joints and flexion of the distal interphalangeal joints. The bilateral, symmetrical nature of the joint involvement, along with the characteristic deformities, strongly suggests \u003Cstrong\u003Erheumatoid arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E as the underlying diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPseudorheumatoid dysplasia\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare genetic condition that typically presents in early childhood with progressive joint stiffness and enlargement. While it can cause joint deformities, the age of onset and clinical course make this diagnosis unlikely in this elderly patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEhlers-Danlos syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a group of inherited connective tissue disorders characterised by joint hypermobility, skin hyperextensibility, and tissue fragility. While it can cause joint problems, it does not typically cause the fixed deformities seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScleroderma\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects the skin and internal organs, causing hardening and tightening of the skin. While it can affect joints, the absence of skin changes and the pattern of joint involvement make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsoriatic arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause joint deformities but typically presents with asymmetric joint involvement and is associated with psoriatic skin changes and nail dystrophy, which are absent in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Swan neck deformity (hyperextension of PIP joint with flexion of DIP joint) is characteristic of longstanding rheumatoid arthritis","Rheumatoid arthritis typically presents with symmetric polyarthritis affecting small joints of hands and feet","The absence of psoriatic skin changes helps differentiate rheumatoid from psoriatic arthritis"],"references":["Coates LC, FitzGerald O, Helliwell PS, Paul C. Psoriasis, psoriatic arthritis, and rheumatoid arthritis: Is all inflammation the same? Seminars in arthritis and rheumatism. 2016;46(3):291-304.","Ridley WE, Xiang H, Han J, Ridley LJ. Swan neck deformity. Journal of Medical Imaging and Radiation Oncology. 2018;62(S1):159-60."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71023"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1532"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14082"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14082"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/16956ad8-287a-4c41-b2de-4b42b5dc239c.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/16956ad8-287a-4c41-b2de-4b42b5dc239c.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":487}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/71023"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-24T16:15:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-24T16:16:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1532"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86754"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"